This article discusses the progress made by the Open Government Partnership (OGP) in promoting transparent, effective, and accountable governance. OGP is a global effort that includes 60 countries and has made over 1000 commitments to improve governance for over two billion people. The United States and its OGP partners have achieved significant milestones, such as the launch of the We the People petitions platform and the creation of online government service centers in Chile. The article also highlights the new U.S. Open Government National Action Plan, which includes commitments to expand open data, modernize the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), increase fiscal transparency, increase corporate transparency, advance citizen engagement and empowerment, and more effectively manage public resources. The plan aims to make government data more accessible, improve FOIA processes, increase transparency of federal spending and corporate ownership, and support civil society globally. The article concludes by mentioning the Administration's commitment to join the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative (EITI) and disclose revenues from geothermal, renewable energy, and timber resources.